Vehicle Diagnostic Reader

Requirements ; Flask, Pyserial.

Overview

Python/OBD-II diagnostic tool built on a genuine ELM327 interface
(PIC18F25K80 + FTDI FT232RL). Talks to the ECU over the standard
OBD-II AT command protocol, decodes PIDs manually at the byte level
(no reliance on a black-box decoding library), and displays live
data via a CLI or Flask dashboard.

Why manual PID decoding

Libraries like python-obd handle decoding for you, but doing it by
hand demonstrates actual understanding of the ELM327 command set and
the OBD-II response format — relevant background for UDS (ISO 14229)
work and automotive cybersecurity roles, where you need to reason
about the protocol at the byte level, not just call a function.

Structure


- obd_serial.py — raw serial layer, handles the AT command handshake

- pid_decoder.py — manual hex-to-value decoding for RPM, speed, coolant temp, throttle

- reader.py — CLI: connect and print live values in a loop

- app.py — Flask dashboard: background polling thread + /api/data endpoint

- templates/index.html — instrument-cluster style live dashboard


Setup

bash
pip install -r requirements.txt

Plug in the ELM327, find your port:

bash
ls /dev/tty.usbserial*

Update the PORT variable at the top of reader.py or app.py to match.

Usage

CLI:

bash
python reader.py

Dashboard:

bash
python app.py

Then open http://localhost:5000 in your browser.

Ignition must be ON (engine doesn't need to be running) for the ECU to respond.

Next steps

- Add more PIDs (fuel trim, MAF, O2 sensor readings)

- Move from OBD-II PIDs to raw CAN bus sniffing (needs a CAN interface like MCP2515 + Arduino, or a USB2CAN adapter) — closer to real UDS/security work

- Log sessions to CSV/SQLite for trip history